{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 04:58:16.268401", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report – SDN Spine–Leaf Lab\n\nSummary of network health\n- Overall status: Unhealthy. End-to-end and even same-leaf L2 connectivity are failing.\n- Scope of impact: All hosts tested (host_1_1, host_1_2, host_2_1, host_2_2) cannot communicate; failures occur both intra-leaf and inter-leaf.\n- Control-plane connectivity: All OVS switches (leaf_1, leaf_2, spine_1) report the SDN controller connection as up (is_connected: true), and are in fail_mode: secure.\n- Data-plane status: All datapath ports on the switches are administratively up (LIVE, 10G-FD). The issue is not a link or interface state problem.\n\nKey observations and test results\n- Reachability tests:\n  - host_1_1 -> host_1_2: Destination Host Unreachable (100% loss).\n  - host_2_1 -> host_2_2: Destination Host Unreachable (100% loss).\n  - host_1_1 -> host_2_1 and host_1_2 -> host_2_2: Destination Host Unreachable (100% loss).\n- Host IP/MAC configuration:\n  - host_1_1: 10.0.0.1/24, MAC fe:b2:1b:62:21:21 (UP).\n  - host_1_2: 10.0.0.2/24, MAC 46:52:65:e6:31:8a (UP).\n  - host_2_1: 10.0.0.9/24, MAC 46:22:97:ca:3c:c8 (UP).\n  - host_2_2: 10.0.0.10/24, MAC d6:61:6c:4e:4e:3d (UP).\n  - ip neigh: host_1_1 and host_1_2 have STALE neighbor entries for each other (indicates ARP activity but traffic not successfully forwarded).\n- Switch status:\n  - All three OVS bridges are connected to controller tcp:20.0.0.100:6633; fail_mode is secure on all.\n  - Port descriptors: All physical ports are LIVE; no errors or down links observed.\n- OpenFlow flow tables (Table 0):\n  - leaf_2: One high-priority drop rule: “priority=100 actions=drop” with very large hit count (n_packets=78000), indicating that essentially all traffic is being dropped at ingress.\n  - leaf_1: A handful of specific L2 rules matching in_port=10 and various dl_src/dl_dst pairs, outputting to ports 9/10/11. Notably:\n    - These source/dest MACs do not match the actual host MACs on leaf_1 (fe:b2:1b:62:21:21 and 46:52:65:e6:31:8a).\n    - The in_port=10 (eth9) and outputs 9/10/11 (eth8/eth9/eth10) do not correspond to the host-facing ports (eth0/eth1 are ports 1 and 2). Hence, host traffic on ports 1/2 will not match these flows.\n    - No table-miss or learning/flood rules are present.\n  - spine_1: Few specific rules with in_port and dl_* matches that also do not reflect the actual host MACs; outputs target ports not aligned to the described links. The rule set is sparse and inconsistent with general L2 forwarding for this topology.\n\nAnomalies detected\n- Controller programming mismatch:\n  - leaf_2 has an explicit blanket drop at priority 100 in table 0, causing pervasive packet loss on that leaf.\n  - leaf_1 and spine_1 have narrowly scoped MAC-to-port rules that:\n    - Reference MAC addresses not present on the hosts.\n    - Use ports that do not align with the host-facing interfaces.\n  - No generic L2 bridging or ARP handling rules (no table-miss actions, no flooding) are present.\n- Port mapping inconsistency:\n  - The installed flows reference in_port/out_port numbers (e.g., 9–11 on leaf_1) that do not correspond to the actual host-facing ports (1–2), suggesting the controller’s topology/port view doesn’t match the actual OVS port mapping.\n- End-hosts correctly configured:\n  - Hosts have valid IPs/masks on 10.0.0.0/24 and show UP interfaces.\n  - ARP cache entries appear but traffic is still “Host Unreachable,” consistent with a data-plane drop in the fabric rather than host misconfiguration.\n\nFault localization\n- Data-plane devices impacted: leaf_2 (most severe, all traffic dropped by policy), leaf_1, and spine_1 (incorrect/insufficient flows).\n- Links/interfaces: All show LIVE; no evidence of physical link or interface-level faults.\n- Control-plane: OVS to controller connectivity is established; fault likely within the controller or its application logic, not transport to controller.\n\nLikely root cause\n- SDN controller misconfiguration or bug causing incorrect OpenFlow programming:\n  - A blanket drop rule on leaf_2 table 0 blocks all forwarding.\n  - Flow entries on leaf_1 and spine_1 do not match actual host MACs or correct host-facing ports, indicating a topology/port mapping mismatch (e.g., controller assumes different port numbering or a different topology/size).\n  - With fail_mode=secure and no appropriate table-miss/learning rules, switches do not flood/learn, so ARP/ICMP are not forwarded, resulting in total connectivity failure.\n\nEvidence highlights\n- Ping results: 100% loss and “Destination Host Unreachable” even within the same leaf (host_1_1 ↔ host_1_2).\n- OVS: is_connected: true and fail_mode: secure on all switches; all ports LIVE.\n- leaf_2 flows: single high-priority drop (n_packets=78000), confirming active dropping.\n- leaf_1 flows: in_port=10 and outputs 9/10/11 with dl_src/dl_dst not matching host MACs; host ports are 1/2.\n- spine_1 flows: sparse, MAC-specific entries mismatched to actual topology.\n\nConclusion\nThe network is in a control-plane induced outage. Physical links and host configurations are fine, but the SDN controller is installing incorrect flows and an explicit drop rule on leaf_2, preventing L2 forwarding across the fabric. The fault is localized to the SDN controller’s flow programming (policy or topology/port mapping logic) impacting leaf_2 most severely and also misprogramming leaf_1 and spine_1.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 20636, "output_tokens": 4261, "total_tokens": 24897, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 20352}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2816}}}
